>but male socialization is brainworms
It is literally not. I would rather not go on a tangent since nobody here can read, but male socialization (as indicated by the name) basically just means how society socializes--trains up a child in the way they should go--people they perceive as male. For the sake of laying this out, male/boy/etc does not mean 'actually male' but 'society perceives as male.'
It does not matter if the child is actually male. If society sees them and recognizes them as one, they will usually undergo male socialization.
This means that society will raise them 'to become men,' and 'as a boy/man.' Not just the parents, society.
This socialization occurs even in an explicitly negative manner, that is not a 'refutation' of male socialization but it 'working as intended.' For example, if a boy is perceived as not 'acting like a normal/ideal man,' he is ostracized and treated like shit for it *because* he is not 'acting like a man.' This is why effeminate boys (or 'boys') are called faggot and beaten up, because the goal is ultimately to get them to stop and to show them that behavior is not acceptable.
Parents are naturally more inclined to push male children into sports, adults react with more irritation or disgust when a male child cries or shows emotion, which in turn is more likely to shape behavior.
There is a reason why lots of trans women have disproportionately male-dominated hobbies or careers and it is because those things were what was socially acceptable for them to get into.
The effects of male socialization are vast, not only affecting hobbies, upbringing and potentially responses to environment, but even stuff like way of speech (men use more profanity than women).
It is very real.

Just because some retards use it as a cudgel to say "you're a man" does not mean that is what the actual original term means.

>before transitioning,
I spent 20-ish years mistakenly thinking I was on the autism spectrum because I struggled with feeling like an android/alien who sucked at human emotions, didn't have a sense of identity, had autistic hyperfixation hobbies, struggled to relate to and connect with others, and felt like I was living in the third person watching myself go through life rather than directly experiencing it. I also hated masculine gender role expectations, but thought it was because I sucked at acting like a normal person, didn't realize it was a gender thing until later. Finally, I also tended to cause uncanny valley effect in other people and often got treated like I was the kind of weirdo I felt like.

>leading up to transition
I finally began to realize that some of these struggles might be gender things, but I wasn't sure if I felt more androgynous or more femme, so I spent a couple of years out as AMAB non-binary with an obviously gender non-conforming presentation. What I eventually realized is that everyone treated me basically like I was still a dude and so rather than my gender dysphoria improving, it got even worse, because now I was making an active effort to escape the prison of masculine gender roles and it wasn't working. Finally I decided to try going full mtf to see if that would work better for me.

>and during your transition
Presenting femme well enough to pass to cis normies and getting on hormones gave me enormous improvements. HRT mostly fixed all the mental health struggles I'd assumed were autism spectrum issues (turns out they were gender dysphoria induced depersonalization instead and HRT fixed it). I also very quickly began to notice a dramatic difference in how friends and acquaintances treated me now that their lizard brains were finally registering me as not a dude. For the first time in my life I feel *normal*, and I feel comfortable and happy with the way people treat me.

I need a second post.

Sleepy Edition

Goal of the thread: At the end of the day, try to write a journal entry listing positive experiences you had throughout the day, cute things you've seen, things that were nice, you get the idea.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

>I simply do not understand how a normal person finds the will to not kill themselves.
I want to latch on to this sentence for a bit of a soapbox regarding suicide, and more generally, how the world is filled with injustice and cruelty.
Many "normal" really don't brush off the harshness of reality so easily. There's about 12 million or so people who will seriously consider suicide, and many more I'm sure will at least entertain the thought. It is a "normal" response to the apparent meaningless, uncaring, and unforgiving world around us.
You're definitely not an entitled snowflake, you're just human, like all the rest of us.

I want to share this video, which got some popularity from Youtube's algorithm a while ago. This is a fairly brief summary of Albert Camus' idea of the absurd, and I hope maybe a few people will find it a useful perspective as I have. He doesn't make any appeals to God, Religion, Philosophy, Morality, Science, Reason etc. etc. When I was at my most suicidal, I wouldn't have given two shits if someone tried to convince me that "Jesus would be sad" or "Your electromagnetic waves won't be in tune with the noosphere when your brain stops functioning." Maybe someone will find it refreshing to hear an argument for Life that accepts only what we know about the world, that it is cold and brutal. At the very least, maybe contemplating the ideas in the video will be a helpful mental exercise to keep your mind off worse thoughts.
It should be noted that, obviously, if you are feeling suicidal, please seek help from a phone call or professional. (The video also notes that Camus makes depression seem much smaller than it actually is)
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=35s4-3T5dJY

>couldn't you just have specific and severe enough bdd to look feminine that you start hrt but not dysphoria
There are two issues with that. The first is, at what is the functional distinction between "bdd to look feminine that improves with physical feminization from HRT" and gender dysphoria?

The second is that, if HRT femboys still had a male gender identity, things like growing breasts would be expected to cause them to become dysphoric. This is what is meant by 'reverse dysphoria' if someone goes on the wrong HRT for their gender identity. Instead of being happy with the changes they get, any changes they get will make them feel bad and dysphoric because of the traits they are losing, which is exactly the opposite reaction to HRT that you're supposed to have.

We know this based on studies of intersex children and infants who had accidents that caused them to be sex reassigned by parents and doctors. Those children were then given hormones in puberty to make them have the puberty that matched the sex they'd been assigned, and additionally, they were not told that this was being done to them.

What happened in cases where the assigned sex did not match the gender identity of those children is that the children usually intuitively figured out and expressed their true gender identity, and they experienced crippling dysphoria when they were forced to have the wrong puberty on enforced HRT, even though they didn't know that's what was being done to them. This body of research is one of the thing that underpinned the development of the informed consent standard for HRT because it showed that if someone goes on the wrong HRT for their gender identity, they will almost certainly voluntarily want to stop taking it well before it would carry significant health risks.

All of that is a long way of saying, if your gender identity isn't that of a woman, you generally will be pretty upset about growing breasts.

1858-1969
The very beginnings of the gay movement were literally steeped in pederastic imagery, since it represented most of homosexuality's recorded history. In Britain and America, the English-originating literary/cultural movement and group of writers known as the Uranians (1858-1930), including Oscar Wilde, Edward Carpenter, Gerard Manley Hopkins and Ralph Chubb, challenged anti-homosexual prejudice through writing on the subject of Ancient Greece or "Greek Love": the love between older males and male youth (adolescents). The Uranian writer John Addington Symonds, inspired by "gay" (pederast) author Walt Whitman, is credited as being the 1st person to use the term "homosexual" in the English-language,[3] in his book A Problem in Greek Ethics, written in 1873 and privately printed in 1901. This work was the 1st to use the term "boy-love", which were both considered as "homosexual" in the Uranian effort to defend and advocate for same-sex love. The American Uranian poet Edward Perry Warren also authored an early defence of same-sex love, in his 3-volume magnum opus (1928-1930), A Defence of Uranian Love. Der Eigene (1896-1932), the very first Gay Journal focused on pederastic writings and photography, and "advocated classical pederasty as a cure for the moral flabbiness of German youth". Scans are available via Wikipedia.[4]

"The issue of love between men and boys has intersected the gay movement since the late nineteenth century, with the rise of the first gay rights movement in Germany. [...] A few (Hans Blüher, for example, famous for his book on the Wandervogel movement) believed that pederasty and male bonding provided a basis for a stronger nation and state - a view that, in a perverted form, found a distorted expression in the militarism of the Hitler Youth."[5]

In her book on the once famous and influential pederast Norman Douglas (see book review), Historian Rachel Hope Cleves quotes from Queer historian Kadji Amin:

"According to Amin, “modern pederasty,” which he defines as age-differentiated sex, was the dominant form of male same-sex practice until the mid-twentieth century. As he reminds readers:
Virtually all late nineteenth- and early twentieth-century canonical authors now remembered as “gay” — including Walt Whitman, Oscar Wilde (whose famous “love that dare not speak its name” was pederasty), Marcel Proust, Jean Cocteau, André Gide, Jean Genet, and even James Baldwin — participated in and, in some cases, wrote about age-differentiated same-sex erotic relations"[7]
In their book chapter "Same Sex, Different Ages: On Pederasty in Gay History," Gert Hekma and D. H. Mader survey the history of recorded male same-sex eroticism through surviving photography artwork. They conclude: "The history of pederasty is to a large extent the history of homosexuality, and vice versa". Reflecting on the dire consequences of expansive definitions of "child pornography,"[8] which can include drawings, animation, and any material featuring real-life persons under 18 years of age even if they are not engaged in sexual activity or remotely naked, they note that the mere possession of much material they and other historians discuss has now become illegal - providing a justification to wield state-power to destroy gay history. 1858-1969
The very beginnings of the gay movement were literally steeped in pederastic imagery, since it represented most of homosexuality's recorded history. In Britain and America, the English-originating literary/cultural movement and group of writers known as the Uranians (1858-1930), including Oscar Wilde, Edward Carpenter, Gerard Manley Hopkins and Ralph Chubb, challenged anti-homosexual prejudice through writing on the subject of Ancient Greece or "Greek Love": the love between older males and male youth (adolescents). The Uranian writer John Addington Symonds, inspired by "gay" (pederast) author Walt Whitman, is credited as being the 1st person to use the term "homosexual" in the English-language,[3] in his book A Problem in Greek Ethics, written in 1873 and privately printed in 1901. This work was the 1st to use the term "boy-love", which were both considered as "homosexual" in the Uranian effort to defend and advocate for same-sex love. The American Uranian poet Edward Perry Warren also authored an early defence of same-sex love, in his 3-volume magnum opus (1928-1930), A Defence of Uranian Love. Der Eigene (1896-1932), the very first Gay Journal focused on pederastic writings and photography, and "advocated classical pederasty as a cure for the moral flabbiness of German youth". Scans are available via Wikipedia.[4]

"The issue of love between men and boys has intersected the gay movement since the late nineteenth century, with the rise of the first gay rights movement in Germany. [...] A few (Hans Blüher, for example, famous for his book on the Wandervogel movement) believed that pederasty and male bonding provided a basis for a stronger nation and state - a view that, in a perverted form, found a distorted expression in the militarism of the Hitler Youth."[5]

A 2021 journal issue entitled "Restoring Intergenerational Dynamics to Queer History"[6] reminds us that intergenerational love and eroticism represent an integral part of Queer history; before terms like "homosexuality" - once designating same-sex attraction - came to be redefined as referring to "androphile" or "adults only." "According to Amin, “modern pederasty,” which he defines as age-differentiated sex, was the dominant form of male same-sex practice until the mid-twentieth century. As he reminds readers:
Virtually all late nineteenth- and early twentieth-century canonical authors now remembered as “gay” — including Walt Whitman, Oscar Wilde (whose famous “love that dare not speak its name” was pederasty), Marcel Proust, Jean Cocteau, André Gide, Jean Genet, and even James Baldwin — participated in and, in some cases, wrote about age-differentiated same-sex erotic relations"[7]
In their book chapter "Same Sex, Different Ages: On Pederasty in Gay History," Gert Hekma and D. H. Mader survey the history of recorded male same-sex eroticism through surviving photography artwork. They conclude: "The history of pederasty is to a large extent the history of homosexuality, and vice versa". Reflecting on the dire consequences of expansive definitions of "child pornography,"[8] which can include drawings, animation, and any material featuring real-life persons under 18 years of age even if they are not engaged in sexual activity or remotely naked, they note that the mere possession of much material they and other historians discuss has now become illegal - providing a justification to wield state-power to destroy gay history. Keith Vacha, a gay writer whose work appeared in Fag Rag, interviewed over 100 homosexuals from the pre-Stonewall generation (born around 1900) for his book Quiet Fire, and noted "a high degree of inter-generational relationships among the men I met" (Quiet Fire, 1985, p. 217). On the basis of his interviews, Vacha attributed this tendency "not so much to preference as to their lack of hesitancy in entering into such age-segregated relationships. The stigma against these kinds of relationships does not appear to be as strong in the gay community as it is in society in general. Furthermore, the stereotype of the older man exchanging status, security and financial favor for the younger man's physical beauty did not hold up. Often, the older man did not have those worldly possessions to offer, suggesting that the relationship was less trade and barter in the presupposed sense." (pp. 217-218).

Homosexuality (including pederasty) remained illegal and strictly taboo until the liberation movements of the 60s. I love the number 5 because it's so closely linked to us. 5 limbs, 5 digits. There are 5 classical elements in Greek, Indian, and Chinese mythology (the 5th gets often shortened to 4 for the Greeks, though). Romans have a numeral dedicated to 5, while most other numbers require multiple digits. Chinese abacus's group numbers by 5 as well. Universally most methods of counting are the same up to the number 5 in a majority of cultures

In addition, there are 5 platonic solids in the 3rd dimension, 6 in the 4th dimension, and then every dimension afterwards only can contain 3. The 1st 4-dimensional platonic solid is coincidentally known as the 5-cell, and when viewed orthographically, it becomes a pentagram!

For a fun lesson in neurology, our brains stop at 4 as the largest grouping we can instantly recognize (known as the Parallel Individuation System). Any number 5 or larger and we switch to a different system in our brain to estimate quantities
